[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Since September 2024, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] The **`VideoFrame`** interface of the Web Codecs API represents a frame of a video.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] A `VideoFrame` object can be created or accessed in a number of ways.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] The `MediaStreamTrackProcessor` breaks a media track into individual `VideoFrame` objects.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] A `VideoFrame` is an image source and has a constructor that accepts any other canvas source ( an `SVGImageElement`, an `HTMLVideoElement`, an `HTMLCanvasElement`, an `ImageBitmap`, an `OffscreenCanvas`, or another `VideoFrame`).
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] This means that a frame can be created from an image or video element.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] A second constructor enables the creation of a `VideoFrame` from its binary pixel representation in an `ArrayBuffer`, a `TypedArray`, or a `DataView`.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Created frames may then turned into a media track, for example with the `MediaStreamTrackGenerator` interface that creates a media track from a stream of frames.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns the pixel format of the `VideoFrame`.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns the width of the `VideoFrame` in pixels, potentially including non-visible padding, and prior to considering potential ratio adjustments.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns the height of the `VideoFrame` in pixels, potentially including non-visible padding, and prior to considering potential ratio adjustments.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns a `DOMRectReadOnly` with the width and height matching `codedWidth` and `codedHeight`.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns a `DOMRectReadOnly` describing the visible rectangle of pixels for this `VideoFrame`.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns the width of the `VideoFrame` when displayed after applying aspect ratio adjustments.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns the height of the `VideoFrame` when displayed after applying aspect ratio adjustments.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns an integer indicating the duration of the video in microseconds.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns an integer indicating the timestamp of the video in microseconds.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns whether the `VideoFrame` is horizontally mirrored.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns the rotation (0, 90, 180, or 270) in degrees clockwise applied to the `VideoFrame`.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Arbitrary numbers (including negatives) are rounded to the next quarter turn.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns the number of bytes required to hold the `VideoFrame` as filtered by options passed into the method.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Copies the contents of the `VideoFrame` to an `ArrayBuffer`.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Creates a new `VideoFrame` object with reference to the same media resource as the original.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Clears all states and releases the reference to the media resource.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] Returns the metadata associated with the `VideoFrame`.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] In the following example frames are returned from a `MediaStreamTrackProcessor`, then encoded.
[src:webcodecs-api/api-videoframe] See the full example and read more about it in the article Video processing with WebCodecs.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] The **`AudioEncoder`** interface of the WebCodecs API encodes `AudioData` objects.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] An integer representing the number of encode queue requests.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] Represents the state of the underlying codec and whether it is configured for encoding.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] Fires to signal a decrease in `AudioEncoder.encodeQueueSize`.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] Returns a promise indicating whether the provided `AudioEncoderConfig` is supported.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] Enqueues a control message to configure the audio encoder for encoding chunks.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] Enqueues a control message to encode a given `AudioData` objects.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] Returns a promise that resolves once all pending messages in the queue have been completed.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] Resets all states including configuration, control messages in the control message queue, and all pending callbacks.
[src:webcodecs-api/audioencoder] Ends all pending work and releases system resources.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In information theory, **data compression**, **source coding**, or **bit-rate reduction** is the process of encoding information using fewer bits than the original representation.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Any particular compression is either lossy or lossless.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossless compression reduces bits by identifying and eliminating statistical redundancy.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] No information is lost in lossless compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossy compression reduces bits by removing unnecessary or less important information.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Typically, a device that performs data compression is referred to as an encoder, and one that performs the reversal of the process (decompression) as a decoder.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The process of reducing the size of a data file is often referred to as data compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In the context of data transmission, it is called source coding: encoding is done at the source of the data before it is stored or transmitted.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Source coding should not be confused with channel coding, for error detection and correction or line coding, the means for mapping data onto a signal.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Data compression algorithms present a space–time complexity trade-off between the bytes needed to store or transmit information, and the computational resources needed to perform the encoding and decoding.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The design of data compression schemes involves balancing the degree of compression, the amount of distortion introduced (when using lossy data compression), and the computational resources or time required to compress and decompress the data.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossless data compression algorithms usually exploit statistical redundancy to represent data without losing any information, so that the process is reversible.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossless compression is possible because most real-world data exhibits statistical redundancy.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] For example, an image may have areas of color that do not change over several pixels; instead of coding "red pixel, red pixel, ..." the data may be encoded as "279 red pixels".
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] This is a basic example of run-length encoding; there are many schemes to reduce file size by eliminating redundancy.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The Lempel–Ziv (LZ) compression methods are among the most popular algorithms for lossless storage.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] DEFLATE is a variation on LZ optimized for decompression speed and compression ratio, but compression can be slow.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In the mid-1980s, following work by Terry Welch, the Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) algorithm rapidly became the method of choice for most general-purpose compression systems.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] LZW is used in GIF images, programs such as PKZIP, and hardware devices such as modems.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] LZ methods use a table-based compression model where table entries are substituted for repeated strings of data.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] For most LZ methods, this table is generated dynamically from earlier data in the input.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The table itself is often Huffman encoded.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Grammar-based codes like this can compress highly repetitive input extremely effectively, for instance, a biological data collection of the same or closely related species, a huge versioned document collection, internet archival, etc.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The basic task of grammar-based codes is constructing a context-free grammar deriving a single string.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Other practical grammar compression algorithms include Sequitur and Re-Pair.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The strongest modern lossless compressors use probabilistic models, such as prediction by partial matching.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The Burrows–Wheeler transform can also be viewed as an indirect form of statistical modelling.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In a further refinement of the direct use of probabilistic modelling, statistical estimates can be coupled to an algorithm called arithmetic coding.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Arithmetic coding is a more modern coding technique that uses the mathematical calculations of a finite-state machine to produce a string of encoded bits from a series of input data symbols.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It can achieve superior compression compared to other techniques, such as the better-known Huffman algorithm.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It uses an internal memory state to avoid the need to perform a one-to-one mapping of individual input symbols to distinct representations that use an integer number of bits, and it clears out the internal memory only after encoding the entire string of data symbols.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Arithmetic coding applies especially well to adaptive data compression tasks where the statistics vary and are context-dependent, as it can be easily coupled with an adaptive model of the probability distribution of the input data.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] An early example of the use of arithmetic coding was in an optional (but not widely used) feature of the JPEG image coding standard.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It has since been applied in various other designs including H.263, H.264/MPEG-4 AVC and HEVC for video coding.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Archive software typically has the ability to adjust the "dictionary size", where a larger size demands more random-access memory during compression and decompression, but compresses more strongly, especially on repeating patterns in files' content.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In the late 1980s, digital images became more common, and standards for lossless image compression emerged.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In the early 1990s, lossy compression methods began to be widely used.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In these schemes, some loss of information is accepted as dropping nonessential detail can save storage space.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] There is a corresponding trade-off between preserving information and reducing size.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossy data compression schemes are designed based on research on how people perceive the data in question.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] For example, the human eye is more sensitive to subtle variations in luminance than it is to the variations in color.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] JPEG image compression works in part by rounding off nonessential bits of information.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] A number of popular compression formats exploit these perceptual differences, including psychoacoustics for sound, and psychovisuals for images and video.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Most forms of lossy compression are based on transform coding, especially the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It was first proposed in 1972 by Nasir Ahmed, who then developed a working algorithm with T.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Rao in 1973, before introducing it in January 1974.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] DCT is the most widely used lossy compression method, and is used in multimedia formats for images (such as JPEG and HEIF), video (such as MPEG, AVC and HEVC) and audio (such as MP3, AAC and Vorbis).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossy image compression is used in digital cameras, to increase storage capacities.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Similarly, DVDs, Blu-ray and streaming video use lossy video coding formats.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossy compression is extensively used in video.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In lossy audio compression, methods of psychoacoustics are used to remove non-audible (or less audible) components of the audio signal.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Compression of human speech is often performed with even more specialized techniques; speech coding is distinguished as a separate discipline from general-purpose audio compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Speech coding is used in internet telephony, for example, audio compression is used for CD ripping and is decoded by the audio players.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossy compression can cause generation loss.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The theoretical basis for compression is provided by information theory and, more specifically, Shannon's source coding theorem; domain-specific theories include algorithmic information theory for lossless compression and rate–distortion theory for lossy compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] These areas of study were essentially created by Claude Shannon, who published fundamental papers on the topic in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Other topics associated with compression include coding theory and statistical inference.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Data compression can be viewed as a special case of data differencing.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] This is the same as considering absolute entropy (corresponding to data compression) as a special case of relative entropy (corresponding to data differencing) with no initial data.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The term *differential compression* is used to emphasize the data differencing connection.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Entropy coding originated in the 1940s with the introduction of Shannon–Fano coding, the basis for Huffman coding which was developed in 1950.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Transform coding dates back to the late 1960s, with the introduction of fast Fourier transform (FFT) coding in 1968 and the Hadamard transform in 1969.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] An important image compression technique is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a technique developed in the early 1970s.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] DCT is the basis for JPEG, a lossy compression format which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) in 1992.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] JPEG greatly reduces the amount of data required to represent an image at the cost of a relatively small reduction in image quality and has become the most widely used image file format.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Its highly efficient DCT-based compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) is a lossless compression algorithm developed in 1984.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It is used in the GIF format, introduced in 1987.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] DEFLATE, a lossless compression algorithm specified in 1996, is used in the Portable Network Graphics (PNG) format.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Wavelet compression, the use of wavelets in image compression, began after the development of DCT coding.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The JPEG 2000 standard was introduced in 2000.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In contrast to the DCT algorithm used by the original JPEG format, JPEG 2000 instead uses discrete wavelet transform (DWT) algorithms.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] JPEG 2000 technology, which includes the Motion JPEG 2000 extension, was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Audio data compression, not to be confused with dynamic range compression, has the potential to reduce the transmission bandwidth and storage requirements of audio data.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Audio compression formats compression algorithms are implemented in software as audio codecs.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In both lossy and lossless compression, information redundancy is reduced, using methods such as coding, quantization, DCT and linear prediction to reduce the amount of information used to represent the uncompressed data.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossy audio compression algorithms provide higher compression and are used in numerous audio applications including Vorbis and MP3.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] These algorithms almost all rely on psychoacoustics to eliminate or reduce fidelity of less audible sounds, thereby reducing the space required to store or transmit them.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The acceptable trade-off between loss of audio quality and transmission or storage size depends upon the application.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] For example, one 640 MB compact disc (CD) holds approximately one hour of uncompressed high fidelity music, less than 2 hours of music compressed losslessly, or 7 hours of music compressed in the MP3 format at a medium bit rate.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] A digital sound recorder can typically store around 200 hours of clearly intelligible speech in 640 MB.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossless audio compression produces a representation of digital data that can be decoded to an exact digital duplicate of the original.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Compression ratios are around 50–60% of the original size, which is similar to those for generic lossless data compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossless codecs use curve fitting or linear prediction as a basis for estimating the signal.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Parameters describing the estimation and the difference between the estimation and the actual signal are coded separately.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] A number of lossless audio compression formats exist.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] See list of lossless codecs for a listing.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Some formats are associated with a distinct system, such as Direct Stream Transfer, used in Super Audio CD and Meridian Lossless Packing, used in DVD-Audio, Dolby TrueHD, Blu-ray and HD DVD.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Some audio file formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction; this allows stripping the correction to easily obtain a lossy file.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, and OptimFROG DualStream.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] When audio files are to be processed, either by further compression or for editing, it is desirable to work from an unchanged original (uncompressed or losslessly compressed).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Processing of a lossily compressed file for some purpose usually produces a final result inferior to the creation of the same compressed file from an uncompressed original.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In addition to sound editing or mixing, lossless audio compression is often used for archival storage, or as master copies.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossy audio compression is used in a wide range of applications.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In addition to standalone audio-only applications of file playback in MP3 players or computers, digitally compressed audio streams are used in most video DVDs, digital television, streaming media on the Internet, satellite and cable radio, and increasingly in terrestrial radio broadcasts.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossy compression typically achieves far greater compression than lossless compression, by discarding less-critical data based on psychoacoustic optimizations.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Psychoacoustics recognizes that not all data in an audio stream can be perceived by the human auditory system.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Most lossy compression reduces redundancy by first identifying perceptually irrelevant sounds, that is, sounds that are very hard to hear.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Typical examples include high frequencies or sounds that occur at the same time as louder sounds.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Those irrelevant sounds are coded with decreased accuracy or not at all.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Due to the nature of lossy algorithms, audio quality suffers a digital generation loss when a file is decompressed and recompressed.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] This makes lossy compression unsuitable for storing the intermediate results in professional audio engineering applications, such as sound editing and multitrack recording.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] However, lossy formats such as MP3 are very popular with end-users as the file size is reduced to 5-20% of the original size and a megabyte can store about a minute's worth of music at adequate quality.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Several proprietary lossy compression algorithms have been developed that provide higher quality audio performance by using a combination of lossless and lossy algorithms with adaptive bit rates and lower compression ratios.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Examples include aptX, LDAC, LHDC, MQA and SCL6.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] To determine what information in an audio signal is perceptually irrelevant, most lossy compression algorithms use transforms such as the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) to convert time domain sampled waveforms into a transform domain, typically the frequency domain.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Once transformed, component frequencies can be prioritized according to how audible they are.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Equal-loudness contours may also be used to weigh the perceptual importance of components.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Models of the human ear-brain combination incorporating such effects are often called psychoacoustic models.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Other types of lossy compressors, such as the linear predictive coding (LPC) used with speech, are source-based coders.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] LPC uses a model of the human vocal tract to analyze speech sounds and infer the parameters used by the model to produce them moment to moment.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] These changing parameters are transmitted or stored and used to drive another model in the decoder, which reproduces the sound.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Lossy formats are often used for the distribution of streaming audio or interactive communication (such as in cell phone networks).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In such applications, the data must be decompressed as the data flows, rather than after the entire data stream has been transmitted.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Not all audio codecs can be used for streaming applications.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Latency is introduced by the methods used to encode and decode the data.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Some codecs will analyze a longer segment, called a *frame*, of the data to optimize efficiency, and then code it in a manner that requires a larger segment of data at one time to decode.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The inherent latency of the coding algorithm can be critical; for example, when there is a two-way transmission of data, such as with a telephone conversation, significant delays may seriously degrade the perceived quality.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In contrast to the speed of compression, which is proportional to the number of operations required by the algorithm, here latency refers to the number of samples that must be analyzed before a block of audio is processed.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In the minimum case, latency is zero samples (e.g., if the coder/decoder simply reduces the number of bits used to quantize the signal).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Time domain algorithms such as LPC also often have low latencies, hence their popularity in speech coding for telephony.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In algorithms such as MP3, however, a large number of samples have to be analyzed to implement a psychoacoustic model in the frequency domain, and latency is on the order of 23 ms.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Speech encoding is an important category of audio data compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The perceptual models used to estimate what aspects of speech a human ear can hear are generally somewhat different from those used for music.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The range of frequencies needed to convey the sounds of a human voice is normally far narrower than that needed for music, and the sound is normally less complex.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] As a result, speech can be encoded at high quality using a relatively low bit rate.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The earliest algorithms used in speech encoding (and audio data compression in general) were the A-law algorithm and the μ-law algorithm.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Early audio research was conducted at Bell Labs.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Chapin Cutler filed the patent on differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In 1973, Adaptive DPCM (ADPCM) was introduced by P.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Perceptual coding was first used for speech coding compression, with linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Initial concepts for LPC date back to the work of Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Perceptual coding is used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3 and AAC.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Discrete cosine transform (DCT), developed by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Rao in 1974, provided the basis for the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3, Dolby Digital, and AAC.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Bradley in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The world's first commercial broadcast automation audio compression system was developed by Oscar Bonello, an engineering professor at the University of Buenos Aires.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] This broadcast automation system was launched in 1987 under the name Audicom.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] A literature compendium for a large variety of audio coding systems was published in the IEEE's *Journal on Selected Areas in Communications* (*JSAC*), in February 1988.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] While there were some papers from before that time, this collection documented an entire variety of finished, working audio coders, nearly all of them using perceptual techniques and some kind of frequency analysis and back-end noiseless coding.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Uncompressed video requires a very high data rate.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Although lossless video compression codecs perform at a compression factor of 5 to 12, a typical H.264 lossy compression video has a compression factor between 20 and 200.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The two key video compression techniques used in video coding standards are the DCT and motion compensation (MC).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Most video coding standards, such as the H.26x and MPEG formats, typically use motion-compensated DCT video coding (block motion compensation).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Most video codecs are used alongside audio compression techniques to store the separate but complementary data streams as one combined package using so-called *container formats*.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Video data may be represented as a series of still image frames.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Such data usually contains abundant amounts of spatial and temporal redundancy.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Video compression algorithms attempt to reduce redundancy and store information more compactly.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Most video compression formats and codecs exploit both spatial and temporal redundancy (e.g., through difference coding with motion compensation).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Similarities can be encoded by only storing differences between e.g., temporally adjacent frames (inter-frame coding) or spatially adjacent pixels (intra-frame coding).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Inter-frame compression (a temporal delta encoding) (re)uses data from one or more earlier or later frames in a sequence to describe the current frame.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Intra-frame coding, on the other hand, uses only data from within the current frame, effectively being still-image compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The intra-frame video coding formats used in camcorders and video editing employ simpler compression that uses only intra-frame prediction.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] This simplifies video editing software, as it prevents a situation in which a compressed frame refers to data that the editor has deleted.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Usually, video compression additionally employs lossy compression techniques like quantization that reduce aspects of the source data that are (more or less) irrelevant to the human visual perception by exploiting perceptual features of human vision.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] For example, small differences in color are more difficult to perceive than are changes in brightness.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Compression algorithms can average a color across these similar areas in a manner similar to those used in JPEG image compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] As in all lossy compression, there is a trade-off between video quality and bit rate, cost of processing the compression and decompression, and system requirements.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Highly compressed video may present visible or distracting artifacts.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Other methods other than the prevalent DCT-based transform formats, such as fractal compression, matching pursuit and the use of a discrete wavelet transform (DWT), have been the subject of some research, but are typically not used in practical products.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Wavelet compression is used in still-image coders and video coders without motion compensation.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Interest in fractal compression seems to be waning, due to recent theoretical analysis showing a comparative lack of effectiveness of such methods.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In inter-frame coding, individual frames of a video sequence are compared from one frame to the next, and the video compression codec records the differences to the reference frame.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] If the frame contains areas where nothing has moved, the system can simply issue a short command that copies that part of the previous frame into the next one.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] If sections of the frame move in a simple manner, the compressor can emit a (slightly longer) command that tells the decompressor to shift, rotate, lighten, or darken the copy.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] This longer command still remains much shorter than data generated by intra-frame compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Usually, the encoder will also transmit a residue signal which describes the remaining, more subtle differences to the reference imagery.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Using entropy coding, these residue signals have a more compact representation than the full signal.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In areas of video with more motion, the compression must encode more data to keep up with the larger number of pixels that are changing.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Commonly, the high-frequency detail of explosions, flames, flocks of animals, and some panning shots will lead to decreases in quality or increases in the variable bitrate.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Many commonly used video compression methods (e.g., those in standards approved by the ITU-T or ISO) share the same basic architecture that dates back to H.261, which was standardized in 1988 by the ITU-T.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] They mostly rely on the DCT, applied to rectangular blocks of neighboring pixels, and temporal prediction using motion vectors, as well as nowadays also an in-loop filtering step.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In the prediction stage, various deduplication and difference-coding techniques are applied that help decorrelate data and describe new data based on already transmitted data.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Then, rectangular blocks of remaining pixel data are transformed to the frequency domain.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In the main lossy processing stage, frequency domain data gets quantized in order to reduce information that is irrelevant to human visual perception.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In the last stage, statistical redundancy gets largely eliminated by an entropy coder, which often applies some form of arithmetic coding.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In an additional in-loop filtering stage, various filters can be applied to the reconstructed image signal.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] By computing these filters also inside the encoding loop, they can help compression because they can be applied to reference material before it gets used in the prediction process and they can be guided using the original signal.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The most popular example are deblocking filters that blur out blocking artifacts from quantization discontinuities at transform block boundaries.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Cherry proposed a run-length encoding bandwidth compression scheme for the transmission of analog television signals.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The DCT, which is fundamental to modern video compression, was introduced by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] H.261, which debuted in 1988, commercially introduced the prevalent basic architecture of video compression technology.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It was the first video coding format based on DCT compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] H.261 was developed by a number of companies, including Hitachi, PictureTel, NTT, BT and Toshiba.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] The most popular video coding standards used for codecs have been the MPEG standards.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] MPEG-1 was developed by the Motion Picture Experts Group (MPEG) in 1991, and it was designed to compress VHS-quality video.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It was succeeded in 1994 by MPEG-2/H.262, which was developed by a number of companies, primarily Sony, Thomson and Mitsubishi Electric.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] MPEG-2 became the standard video format for DVD and SD digital television.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It was also developed by a number of companies, primarily Mitsubishi Electric, Hitachi and Panasonic.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] H.264/MPEG-4 AVC was developed in 2003 by a number of organizations, primarily Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] AVC commercially introduced the modern context-adaptive binary arithmetic coding (CABAC) and context-adaptive variable-length coding (CAVLC) algorithms.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Genetics compression algorithms are the latest generation of lossless algorithms that compress data (typically sequences of nucleotides) using both conventional compression algorithms and genetic algorithms adapted to the specific datatype.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] In 2012, a team of scientists from Johns Hopkins University published a genetic compression algorithm that does not use a reference genome for compression.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] HAPZIPPER was tailored for HapMap data and achieves over 20-fold compression (95% reduction in file size), providing 2- to 4-fold better compression and is less computationally intensive than the leading general-purpose compression utilities.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] For this, Chanda, Elhaik, and Bader introduced MAF-based encoding (MAFE), which reduces the heterogeneity of the dataset by sorting SNPs by their minor allele frequency, thus homogenizing the dataset.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] Other algorithms developed in 2009 and 2013 (DNAZip and GenomeZip) have compression ratios of up to 1200-fold—allowing 6 billion basepair diploid human genomes to be stored in 2.5 megabytes (relative to a reference genome or averaged over many genomes).
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It is estimated that the total amount of data that is stored on the world's storage devices could be further compressed with existing compression algorithms by a remaining average factor of 4.5:1.
[src:webcodecs-api/data-compression] It is estimated that the combined technological capacity of the world to store information provides 1,300 exabytes of hardware digits in 2007, but when the corresponding content is optimally compressed, this only represents 295 exabytes of Shannon information.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] A **frame** is a digital data transmission unit in computer networking and telecommunications.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] In packet switched systems, a frame is a simple container for a single network packet.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] In other telecommunications systems, a frame is a repeating structure supporting time-division multiplexing.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] A frame typically includes frame synchronization features consisting of a sequence of bits or symbols that indicate to the receiver the beginning and end of the payload data within the stream of symbols or bits it receives.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] If a receiver is connected to the system during frame transmission, it ignores the data until it detects a new frame synchronization sequence.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] In the OSI model of computer networking, a frame is the protocol data unit at the data link layer.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] Frames are the result of the final layer of encapsulation before the data is transmitted over the physical layer.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] A frame is "the unit of transmission in a link layer protocol, and consists of a link layer header followed by a packet." Each frame is separated from the next by an interframe gap.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] A frame is a series of bits generally composed of frame synchronization bits, the packet payload, and a frame check sequence.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] Examples are Ethernet frames, Wi-Fi frames, 4G frames, Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) frames, Fibre Channel frames, and V.42 modem frames.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] Often, frames of several different sizes are nested inside each other.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] In telecommunications, specifically in time-division multiplex (TDM) and time-division multiple access (TDMA) variants, a frame is a cyclically repeated data block that consists of a fixed number of time slots, one for each logical TDM channel or TDMA transmitter.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] In this context, a frame is typically an entity at the physical layer.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] TDM application examples are SONET/SDH and the ISDN circuit-switched B-channel, while TDMA examples are Circuit Switched Data used in early cellular voice services.
[src:webcodecs-api/frame-networking] The frame is also an entity for time-division duplex, where the mobile terminal may transmit during some time slots and receive during others.
[src:webcodecs-api/videodecoder] The **`VideoDecoder`** interface of the WebCodecs API decodes chunks of video.
[src:webcodecs-api/videodecoder] An integer representing the number of queued decode requests.
[src:webcodecs-api/videodecoder] Fires to signal a decrease in `VideoDecoder.decodeQueueSize`.
[src:webcodecs-api/videodecoder] Returns a promise indicating whether the provided `VideoDecoderConfig` is supported.
[src:webcodecs-api/videodecoder] Enqueues a control message to configure the video decoder for decoding chunks.
[src:webcodecs-api/videodecoder] Enqueues a control message to decode a given chunk of video.
[src:webcodecs-api/videoencoder] The **`VideoEncoder`** interface of the WebCodecs API encodes `VideoFrame` objects into `EncodedVideoChunk`s.
[src:webcodecs-api/videoencoder] Fires to signal a decrease in `VideoEncoder.encodeQueueSize`.
[src:webcodecs-api/videoencoder] Returns a promise indicating whether the provided `VideoEncoderConfig` is supported.
[src:webcodecs-api/videoencoder] Asynchronously prepares the encoder to accept video frames for encoding with the specified parameters.
[src:webcodecs-api/videoencoder] Returns a promise that resolves once all pending encodes have been completed.
[src:webcodecs-api/videoencoder] Cancels all pending encodes and callbacks.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The **WebCodecs API** enables web developers to encode and decode video and audio in the browser efficiently (using hardware acceleration) and with very low-level control (processing on a per-frame basis).
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] It is useful for web applications that do heavy media processing, or which require low-level control over the way media is encoded.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] This includes browser-based video and audio editing, as well as live-streaming and video conferencing.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The WebCodecs API provides browser-native interfaces to represent raw video frames, encoded video frames, as well as raw and encoded audio.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The WebCodecs API also introduces the `VideoDecoder` and `VideoEncoder` interfaces, which transform `EncodedVideoChunk` objects into `VideoFrame` objects and vice-versa.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Likewise, the WebCodecs API also introduces the `AudioDecoder` and `AudioEncoder` interfaces, which transform `EncodedAudioChunk` objects into `AudioData` objects and vice-versa.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Generally there is a 1:1 correspondence between the raw and encoded versions of each media type.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Decoding a number of `EncodedVideoChunk` objects will yield the same number of `VideoFrame` objects (and this is also true for audio).
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] A `VideoFrame` represents a video frame, and is tied to actual pixel data on the device's graphics memory, as well as metadata such as the timestamp and duration (in microseconds), format and resolution.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] A `VideoFrame` can be constructed from any image source, and can also be rendered to a `Canvas` using any of the canvas rendering methods.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] `EncodedVideoChunk` represents the encoded (compressed) version of the same frame, tied to binary data in regular memory and the same metadata.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The only difference is that it has one additional field: `type`, which can be "key" or "delta", representing whether or not it corresponds to a key frame.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] An `EncodedVideoChunk` typically stores 10 to 100 times less data than its corresponding raw `VideoFrame`.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] An `AudioData` object represents a number of individual audio samples (1024 is a typical number).
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Audio sample data can be extracted as a `Float32Array` via the `copyTo` method.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] There is no direct integration with the Web Audio API; however, the extracted `Float32Array` samples can be copied directly into a `AudioBuffer` for playback.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Likewise, the `EncodedAudioChunk` represents the encoded (compressed) version of an `AudioData` object, containing compressed audio sample data.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The WebCodecs API uses an asynchronous processing model.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Each instance of an encoder or decoder maintains an internal, independent processing queue.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] When queueing a substantial number of encoded chunks for decoding or frames/samples for encoding, it's important to keep this model in mind.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Methods named `configure()`, `encode()`, `decode()`, and `flush()` operate asynchronously by appending control messages to the end of the queue, while methods named `reset()` and `close()` synchronously abort all pending work and purge the processing queue.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] After `reset()`, more work may be queued following a call to `configure()`, but `close()` is a permanent operation.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] These methods work for both Audio and Video decoders/encoders.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The `flush()` method can be used to wait for the completion of all work that was pending at the time `flush()` was called.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] However, it should generally only be called once all desired work is queued — it is not intended to force progress at regular intervals.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Calling it unnecessarily will affect encoder quality and cause decoders to require the next input to be a key frame.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] A codec is a specific algorithm for encoding (compressing) and decoding (decompressing) video and audio.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] There are several industry standard codecs for video, and a separate set of codecs for audio.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Commonly used on YouTube and in WebM files.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The newest open source codec, with better compression than VP9.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Broad decoder support; hardware encoder support is still limited.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Better compression than H.264, but with significant gaps in browser support outside of Apple platforms.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The recommended choice for most WebCodecs audio encoding.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Broadly supported for decoding, but not available as an encoder in WebCodecs.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The WebCodecs specification supports a particular set of codecs, and individual devices and browsers may only support a subset of those.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Encoders and decoders must be configured with fully specified codec strings (such as `"vp09.00.40.08.00"` for VP9 or `"avc1.4d0034"` for H.264) instead of ambiguous codec names like `"vp9"` or `"h264"`.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The Codec selection guide provides guidance on choosing an appropriate codec string (see the Codec Support Table (webcodecsfundamentals.org) for a complete list of codec strings and their browser support).
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The WebCodecs API only deals with encoding and decoding, with encoded chunks just representing binary data.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] It does not provide a built-in way to read `EncodedVideoChunk` objects from a video file, or write them to a playable video file.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Reading encoded chunks from a video file is a completely different process called demuxing, and to fetch `EncodedVideoChunk` objects from a video file, you will need to use a demuxing library such as Mediabunny or web-demuxer.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] These libraries will follow the video container specifications (e.g., webm, mp4) to extract the track data and byte offsets for each encoded chunk, and provide methods for extracting the actual chunks from the raw file.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Likewise, to write to a playable video file, you will need a muxing library, with Mediabunny being the primary option.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Muxing libraries handle formatting the binary encoded data, and placing it in the correct byte position in the output file stream according to the container specification, so that the output video is playable.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] You can find more information on muxing and demuxing in the Muxing and Demuxing guide (webcodecsfundamentals.org).
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] A brief primer on video processing, covering codecs and containers, muxing and demuxing, and conceptual information that explains how the WebCodecs API implements these concepts.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] In depth guide to how to actually use the WebCodecs API, including how to instantiate and configure encoders and decoders, how to create and consume video frames, and how to extract samples from `AudioData`.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] The WebCodecs API requires codec strings — precise identifiers that specify not just the codec family but also the profile, level, and other parameters.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] This guide explains how codec strings work and how to choose the right codec for common use cases.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Represents codec-specific encoded audio bytes.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Represents codec-specific encoded video bytes.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Represents a frame of unencoded video data.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Represents the color space of a video frame.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Unpacks and decodes image data, giving access to the sequence of frames in an animated image.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] Represents the list of tracks available in the image.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] To instantiate a `VideoEncoder`, we pass an object that specifies a callback function that will be called when `EncodedVideoChunk` instances are available for processing, and an error function that will be called if there are errors.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] You then need to configure the encoder with the codec parameter and various other fields.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] You can then start encoding frames to the encoder.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] You can construct a `VideoFrame` from a `Canvas`.
[src:webcodecs-api/webcodecs-api] See Using the WebCodecs API for more examples.
